CODE 1.a

# read in data and assign column 1 to x and column 2 to y
dat <- read.csv("USPop.csv")
x <- dat$Year
y <- dat$Population
n <- length(x)
# calculate the r using formula
r <- sum(((x - mean(x)) / sd(x) * (y - mean(y)) / sd(y)) / (n - 1))
r
## [1] 0.9585941

CODE 1.b

# t statistic and p value
t <- r * sqrt((n - 2) / (1 - r ^ 2))
pt(t, df = n - 2, lower.tail = F) * 2
## [1] 6.265315e-13
# z statistic and p value
z <- log((1 + r) / (1 - r)) / 2
pnorm(z, sd = 1 / sqrt(n - 3), lower.tail = F)
## [1] 3.24609e-18

ANSWER 1.b

Both p values are smaller than significance level of 0.05, meaning that we can reject the null of \(\rho=\rho_0=0\).

CODE 1.c

cor(x, y, method = "spearman")
## [1] 1

ANSWER 1.c

Spearman correlation is larger than pearson correlation. This might be because Spearmans rank correlation is less sensitive to the assumption of normality than the Pearson correlation.

CODE 1.d

# corruption
y.corrup <- y
y.corrup[x == 2010] <- -1 * y[x == 2010]
# Pearson
cor(x, y.corrup)
## [1] 0.3898808
# Spearman
cor(x, y.corrup, m = "sp")
## [1] 0.75

ANSWER 1.d

Pearson correlation drops a lot from original value but spearman correlation is relatively robust, which drops less. This might be because Spearmans rank correlation is less sensitive to outlying values than the Pearson correlation.

CODE 2.g

# standard error of b
b.se <- sqrt(sum((y - y.esti) ^ 2) / (n - 2) / sum((x - mean(x)) ^ 2))
# t statistic
t <- b / b.se
t
## [1] 19.00618
# p value
pt(t, df = n - 2, lower.tail = F) * 2
## [1] 1.121268e-69

ANSWER 2.g

P value is smaller than significance level of 0.05, meaning we can reject the null of \(\beta=0\)

CODE 2.h

b + qt(0.975, n - 2) * b.se

# lower bound of 95% CI
b - qt(0.975, n - 2) * b.se
## [1] 0.4610188

CODE 3

set.seed(1)
son.esti.mean <- numeric()
for (i in 1:1000) {
  # sample 1000 pairs with replacement from original data
  fatherson_sample <-
    father.son[sample(1:1078, 1078, replace = T), 1:2]
  # fit a linear model
  sample_model <-
    lm(fatherson_sample$sheight ~ fatherson_sample$fheight)
  # a is the intercept and b is the coefficient of the independent variable
  a <- sample_model$coefficients[1]
  b <- sample_model$coefficients[2]
  # calculate the mean of the estimated son height
  son.esti <- a + b * fatherson_sample$fheight
  son.esti.mean[i] <- mean(son.esti)
}
# mean of the 1000 values
mean(son.esti.mean)
## [1] 68.68446
# standard dev. of the 1000 values
sd(son.esti.mean)
## [1] 0.08550514
# sort and denote
h_25 <- sort(son.esti.mean)[25]
h_975 <- sort(son.esti.mean)[975]
h_25
## [1] 68.51066
h_975
## [1] 68.85346
